Bug-hunting tip: watch out for & and | when you mean && and || The operators && and || are Boolean operators: they work on expressions that are true or false. But there are two more operators, not covered in this course, namely & and |. Quite often, if you use & where you intend &&, the result will appear to be the same, but beware, they are not the same thing at all. & is the "bitwise AND" operator and works on pairs of integers (actually, on the integers expressed in binary digits). Similarly, | is "bitwise OR" and likewise works on integer values. As you can imagine, spotting that you used "&" where you should have used "&&" can be a very hard bug to find. The same goes for cases where you used "|" and you should have used "||". In Julia the type system prevents many but not all of these problems, so when your code is returning strange values but no errors, be aware of the bitwise-for-Boolean bug!

SIR models formalise what is probably the simplest possible way to think of an epidemic:
S - Still at Risk... Susceptible... S(t) function of time
S(0) - S at start
I - Infected people... I(t)... Assume that I(0) > 0 (i.e. epidemic must begin)
R = Removed... R(t)
may be recovered, still ill or dead.
S,I,R may not be integers... may be fractional real numbers.
SI = number of meetings of Susceptible and Infected
lambda is the proportionality constant
lambda * SI = rate of new infections
gamma = recovery constant
gamma * I = recovery rate
A ROW... eg... [ s i r ]
Creates a Row of data... can be inserted into 2D matrix
resultvals = Array(Float64, nsteps+1, 3)
